Macros">Related Macros</a></li></ul></section><div id="rustdoc-modnav"><h2><a href="index.html">In device_<wbr>kit::<wbr>led_<wbr>strip</a></h2></div></div></nav><div class="sidebar-resizer" title="Drag to resize sidebar"></div><main><div class="width-limiter"><section id="main-content" class="content"><div class="main-heading"><div class="rustdoc-breadcrumbs"><a href="../index.html">device_kit</a>::<wbr><a href="index.html">led_strip</a></div><h1>Macro <span class="macro">led_<wbr>strips</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#987-989">Source</a> </span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>macro_rules! led_strips {
    ($($tt:tt)*) =&gt; { ... };
}</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Macro to generate multiple LED strip and panel struct types that share a single
<a href="../index.html#glossary" title="mod device_kit">PIO resource</a> (includes syntax details).</p>
<p>This page provides the primary documentation and examples for configuring strip/panel
groups that share a PIO resource.</p>
<p><strong>After reading the examples below, see also:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="led_strip_generated/struct.LedStripGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::led_strip_generated::LedStripGenerated"><code>LedStripGenerated</code></a> — Sample LED <strong>strip</strong> type showing all methods and associated constants</li>
<li><a href="../led2d/led2d_generated/struct.Led2dGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::led2d_generated::Led2dGenerated"><code>Led2dGenerated</code></a> — Sample LED <strong>panel</strong> type showing all methods and associated constants</li>
<li><a href="../macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a> — Alternative macro to generate a single LED strip type. Consumes a PIO resource.</li>
<li><a href="../led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> — Alternative macro to generate a single LED panel type. Consumes a PIO resource.</li>
</ul>
<p>Use this macro when your project has multiple LED strips or panels
that should share a single PIO resource.
If you only need a single strip or panel, prefer <a href="../macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a>
or <a href="../macro.led2d.html" title="macro device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> for simpler configuration.</p>
<p>We’ll start with a complete example below, then describe the required and
optional fields in detail.</p>
<h2 id="example-connect-three-led-stripspanels-to-one-pio-resource"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#example-connect-three-led-stripspanels-to-one-pio-resource">§</a>Example: Connect Three LED Strips/Panels to One PIO Resource</h2>
<p>This example creates three LED strips/panels on GPIO0, GPIO3, and GPIO4,
all sharing PIO0. It demonstrates showing a pattern on the first two strips
and animating text on the 2D panel.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO0 strip preview" /></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO3 strip preview" /></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO4 panel preview" /></p>

<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="kw">use </span>device_kit::{<span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>, led2d::Frame2d, led2d::Led2dFont, led2d::layout::LedLayout, led_strip::{Current, Frame1d, Gamma, colors, led_strips}};
<span class="kw">use </span>embassy_time::Duration;

<span class="comment">// Our 2D panel is two 12x4 panels stacked vertically.
</span><span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X4: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">48</span>, <span class="number">12</span>, <span class="number">4</span>&gt; = LedLayout::serpentine_column_major();
<span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X8: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">96</span>, <span class="number">12</span>, <span class="number">8</span>&gt; = LED_LAYOUT_12X4.combine_v(LED_LAYOUT_12X4);
<span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X8_ROTATED: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">96</span>, <span class="number">8</span>, <span class="number">12</span>&gt; = LED_LAYOUT_12X8.rotate_cw();

<span class="macro">led_strips!</span> {
    pio: PIO0,                          <span class="comment">// Optional; defaults to PIO0.
    </span>LedStrips0 {                        <span class="comment">// Name for this group of LED strips/panels. Can provide visibility modifier
        // 1. a 8-LED strip on GPIO0
        </span>Gpio0LedStrip: {                <span class="comment">// Exact struct name for this strip.
            </span>pin: PIN_0,                 <span class="comment">// GPIO pin for LED data signal.
            </span>len: <span class="number">8</span>,                     <span class="comment">// 8 LEDs on this strip.
            </span>max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">25</span>), <span class="comment">// Every strip/panel requires an electrical current budget.
        </span>},
        <span class="comment">// 2. a 48-LED strip on GPIO3
        </span>Gpio3LedStrip: {
            pin: PIN_3,
            len: <span class="number">48</span>,
            max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">75</span>),
            gamma: Gamma::Gamma2_2,     <span class="comment">// Optional; color correction (default, Gamma::Gamma2_2).
            </span>max_frames: <span class="number">1</span>,              <span class="comment">// Optional; default 16 frames.
            </span>dma: DMA_CH11,              <span class="comment">// Optional; auto-assigned by strip order.
        </span>},
        <span class="comment">// 3. a 96-LED 2D panel on GPIO4
        </span>Gpio4Led2d: {
            pin: PIN_4,
            len: <span class="number">96</span>,
            max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">250</span>),
            max_frames: <span class="number">2</span>,
            led2d: {                    <span class="comment">// Optional panel configuration for 2D displays.
                </span>led_layout: LED_LAYOUT_12X8_ROTATED, <span class="comment">// Two 12×4 panels stacked and rotated.
                </span>font: Led2dFont::Font4x6Trim, <span class="comment">// 4x6 pixel font without the usual 1 pixel spacing.
            </span>}
        },
    }
}

<span class="kw">async fn </span>example(spawner: Spawner) -&gt; <span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>&lt;Infallible&gt; {
    <span class="kw">let </span>p = embassy_rp::init(Default::default());

    <span class="comment">// Create instances of two LED strips and one panel.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span>(gpio0_led_strip, gpio3_led_strip, gpio4_led2d) = LedStrips0::new(
        p.PIO0, p.PIN_0, p.DMA_CH0, p.PIN_3, p.DMA_CH11, p.PIN_4, p.DMA_CH2, spawner,
    )<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="macro">info!</span>(<span class="string">"Setting GPIO0 to white, GPIO3 to alternating blue/gray, GPIO4 to Go Go animation"</span>);

    <span class="comment">// Turn on all-white on GPIO0 strip.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span>frame_gpio0 = Frame1d::filled(colors::WHITE);
    gpio0_led_strip.write_frame(frame_gpio0).<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>; <span class="comment">// Display the frame (until replaced)

    // Alternate blue/gray on GPIO3 strip.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_gpio3 = Frame1d::new();
    <span class="kw">for </span>pixel_index <span class="kw">in </span><span class="number">0</span>..Gpio3LedStrip::LEN {
        frame_gpio3[pixel_index] = [colors::BLUE, colors::GRAY][pixel_index % <span class="number">2</span>];
    }
    gpio3_led_strip.write_frame(frame_gpio3).<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>;  <span class="comment">// Display the frame (until replaced)

    // Animate "Go Go" text on GPIO4 2D panel.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_go_top = Frame2d::new();
    gpio4_led2d.write_text_to_frame(<span class="string">"Go"</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[], <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>frame_go_top)<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_go_bottom = Frame2d::new();
    gpio4_led2d.write_text_to_frame(
        <span class="string">"\nGo"</span>,
        <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[colors::HOT_PINK, colors::LIME],
        <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>frame_go_bottom,
    )<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="kw">let </span>frame_duration = Duration::from_secs(<span class="number">1</span>);
    gpio4_led2d
        .animate([
            (frame_go_top, frame_duration),
            (frame_go_bottom, frame_duration),
        ])
        .<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>; <span class="comment">// Loop animation (until replaced)

    </span>future::pending::&lt;<span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>&lt;Infallible&gt;&gt;().<span class="kw">await </span><span class="comment">// Run forever
</span>}</code></pre></div><h2 id="configuration"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#configuration">§</a>Configuration</h2><h3 id="shared-pio-resource"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#shared-pio-resource">§</a>Shared PIO Resource</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>pio</code> — PIO peripheral to use (default: <code>PIO0</code>). This consumes one PIO resource for the
group and is shared across all strips/panels in the macro invocation.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="required-fields-per-strippanel"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#required-fields-per-strippanel">§</a>Required Fields per Strip/Panel</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>pin</code> — GPIO pin for LED data</li>
<li><code>len</code> — Number of LEDs (pixels)</li>
<li><code>max_current</code> — Electrical current budget per strip (required; no default)</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="optional-fields-per-strippanel"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#optional-fields-per-strippanel">§</a>Optional Fields per Strip/Panel</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>dma</code> — DMA channel (default: auto-assigned by strip order)</li>
<li><code>gamma</code> — Gamma correction curve (default: <code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_frames</code> — Maximum number of animation frames (default: 16 frames)</li>
<li><code>led2d</code> — Marks this strip as a 2D LED panel and enables 2D rendering support (optional, see below).
Detailed 2D rendering, examples, and animation support are documented
in the <a href="../led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d</code> module</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="2d-panel-configuration-led2d"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#2d-panel-configuration-led2d">§</a>2D Panel Configuration (<code>led2d</code>)</h3>
<p>If a strip represents a rectangular LED panel rather than a linear strip,
add a <code>led2d</code> configuration block to describe its geometry.</p>
<p>Required fields:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>led_layout</code> — Physical layout mapping (defines the panel size). See <a href="../led2d/layout/struct.LedLayout.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::layout::LedLayout"><code>LedLayout</code></a> for details.</li>
<li><code>font</code> — Built-in font for text rendering. See <a href="../led2d/enum.Led2dFont.html" title="enum device_kit::led2d::Led2dFont"><code>Led2dFont</code></a> for available fonts.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>led_layout</code> value must be a const so its dimensions can be derived at compile time.</p>
<h2 id="capacity-and-board-capabilities"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#capacity-and-board-capabilities">§</a>Capacity and Board Capabilities</h2>
<p>The <code>led_strips!</code> macro is designed to <strong>fully utilize the PIO resources</strong>
of supported Pico boards.</p>
<p>Each <code>led_strips!</code> invocation can drive up to <strong>4 LED strips or panels</strong>
while sharing a single PIO resource. This lets you consolidate multiple
LED outputs efficiently instead of consuming one PIO per strip.</p>
<p>Each invocation consumes exactly one PIO resource.</p>
<p>On supported boards, this enables the maximum practical LED capacity:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pico 1</strong> provides <strong>2 PIO resources</strong>, allowing up to <strong>8 LED strips or panels</strong></li>
<li><strong>Pico 2</strong> provides <strong>3 PIO resources</strong>, allowing up to <strong>12 LED strips or panels</strong></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="current-limiting"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#current-limiting">§</a>Current Limiting</h2>
<p>The <code>max_current</code> field automatically scales brightness to stay within your electrical current budget.</p>
<p>Each WS2812 LED is assumed to draw 60 mA at full brightness. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>16 LEDs × 60 mA = 960 mA at full brightness</li>
<li>With <code>max_current: Current::Milliamps(1000)</code>, all LEDs fit at 100% brightness</li>
<li>With the default electrical current limit (250 mA), the generated <code>MAX_BRIGHTNESS</code> limits LEDs to ~26% brightness</li>
</ul>
<p>The electrical current limit is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<p><strong>Powering LEDs from the Pico’s pin 40 (VBUS):</strong> Pin 40 is the USB 5 V rail pass-through, but the Pico itself has practical electrical current limits — the USB connector, cable, and internal circuitry aren’t designed for heavy loads. Small LED panels (a few hundred mA) can usually power from pin 40 with a decent USB supply; for larger loads (1 A+), use a separate 5 V supply and share ground with the Pico.</p>
<h2 id="color-correction-gamma"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#color-correction-gamma">§</a>Color Correction (Gamma)</h2>
<p>The <code>gamma</code> field applies a color response curve to make colors look more natural:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="enum.Gamma.html#variant.Linear" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Linear"><code>Gamma::Linear</code></a> — No correction (raw values)</li>
<li><a href="enum.Gamma.html#variant.Gamma2_2" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Gamma2_2"><code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code></a> — sRGB-like curve (default; often looks most natural)</li>
</ul>
<p>The gamma curve is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<h2 id="related-macros"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#related-macros">§</a>Related Macros</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href="../macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a> — For a single 1-dimensional LED strip (includes examples)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="../led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> — For 2-dimensional LED panels</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div></details></section></div></main></body></html>

href="index.html">led_strip</a></div><h1>Struct <span class="struct">Frame1d</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#392">Source</a> </span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>pub struct Frame1d&lt;const N: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt;(pub [<a class="type" href="type.RGB8.html" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>1D pixel array used to describe LED strip patterns.</p>
<p>See the <a href="index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip">led_strip module documentation</a> for usage examples.</p>
<p>Frames deref to <code>[RGB8; N]</code>, so you can mutate pixels directly before passing them to the generated strip’s <code>write_frame</code> method.</p>
</div></details><h2 id="fields" class="fields section-header">Tuple Fields<a href="#fields" class="anchor">§</a></h2><span id="structfield.0" class="structfield section-header"><a href="#structfield.0" class="anchor field">§</a><code>0: [<a class="type" href="type.RGB8.html" title="type device_kit::led_strip::RGB8">RGB8</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]</code></span><h2 id="implementations" class="section-header">Implementations<a href="#implementations" class="anchor">§</a></h2><div id="implementations-list"><details class="toggle implementors-toggle" open><summary><section id="impl-Frame1d%3CN%3E" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#394-413">Source</a><a href="#impl-Frame1d%3CN%3E" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;const N: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt; <a class="struct" href="struct.Frame1d.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::Frame1d">Frame1d</a>&lt;N&gt;</h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle" open><summary><section id="associatedconstant.LEN" class="associatedconstant"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#396">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub const <a href="#associatedconstant.LEN" class="constant">LEN</a>: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a> = N</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Number of LEDs in this frame.</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.new" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#402-404">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub const fn <a href="#method.new" class="fn">new</a>() -&gt; Self</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Create a new blank (all black) frame.</p>
<p>See the <a href="index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip">led_strip module documentation</a> for usage examples.</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.filled" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#410-412">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub const fn <a href="#method.filled" class="fn">filled</a>(color: <a class="type" href="type.RGB8.html" title="type device_kit::led_strip::RGB8">RGB8</a>) -&gt; Self</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Create a frame filled with a single color.</p>
<p>See the <a href="index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip">led_strip module documentation</a> for usage examples.</p>
</div></details></div></details></div><details class="toggle big-toggle" open><summary><h2 id="deref-methods-%5BRGB8;+N%5D" class="section-header"><span>Methods from <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/ops/deref/trait.Deref.html" title="trait core::ops::deref::Deref">Deref</a>&lt;Target = [<a class="type" href="type.RGB8.html" title="type device_kit::led_strip::RGB8">RGB8</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]&gt;</span><a href="#deref-methods-%5BRGB8;+N%5D" class="anchor">§</a></h2></summary><div id="deref-methods-%5BRGB8;+N%5D-1" class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.as_ascii" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/ascii.rs.html#21">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.as_ascii" class="fn">as_ascii</a>(&amp;self) -&gt; <a class="enum" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/option/enum.Option.html" title="enum core::option::Option">Option</a>&lt;&amp;[<a class="enum" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/ascii/ascii_char/enum.AsciiChar.html" title="enum core::ascii::ascii_char::AsciiChar">AsciiChar</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]&gt;</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>ascii_char</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Converts this array of bytes into an array of ASCII characters,
or returns <code>None</code> if any of the characters is non-ASCII.</p>
<h5 id="examples"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#examples">§</a>Examples</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="attr">#![feature(ascii_char)]

</span><span class="kw">const </span>HEX_DIGITS: [std::ascii::Char; <span class="number">16</span>] =
    <span class="kw-2">*</span><span class="string">b"0123456789abcdef"</span>.as_ascii().unwrap();

<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(HEX_DIGITS[<span class="number">1</span>].as_str(), <span class="string">"1"</span>);
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(HEX_DIGITS[<span class="number">10</span>].as_str(), <span class="string">"a"</span>);</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.as_ascii_unchecked" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/ascii.rs.html#39">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub unsafe fn <a href="#method.as_ascii_unchecked" class="fn">as_ascii_unchecked</a>(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;[<a class="enum" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/ascii/ascii_char/enum.AsciiChar.html" title="enum core::ascii::ascii_char::AsciiChar">AsciiChar</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>ascii_char</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Converts this array of bytes into an array of ASCII characters,
without checking whether they’re valid.</p>
<h5 id="safety"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#safety">§</a>Safety</h5>
<p>Every byte in the array must be in <code>0..=127</code>, or else this is UB.</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.as_slice" class="method"><span class="rightside"><span class="since" title="Stable since Rust version 1.57.0">1.57.0</span> · <a class="src" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#593">Source</a></span><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.as_slice" class="fn">as_slice</a>(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a></h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Returns a slice containing the entire array. Equivalent to <code>&amp;s[..]</code>.</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.as_mut_slice" class="method"><span class="rightside"><span class="since" title="Stable since Rust version 1.57.0">1.57.0</span> · <a class="src" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#601">Source</a></span><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.as_mut_slice" class="fn">as_mut_slice</a>(&amp;mut self) -&gt; &amp;mut <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a></h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Returns a mutable slice containing the entire array. Equivalent to
<code>&amp;mut s[..]</code>.</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.each_ref" class="method"><span class="rightside"><span class="since" title="Stable since Rust version 1.77.0">1.77.0</span> · <a class="src" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#631">Source</a></span><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.each_ref" class="fn">each_ref</a>(&amp;self) -&gt; [<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.reference.html">&amp;T</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Borrows each element and returns an array of references with the same
size as <code>self</code>.</p>
<h5 id="example"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#example">§</a>Example</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="kw">let </span>floats = [<span class="number">3.1</span>, <span class="number">2.7</span>, -<span class="number">1.0</span>];
<span class="kw">let </span>float_refs: [<span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>f64; <span class="number">3</span>] = floats.each_ref();
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(float_refs, [<span class="kw-2">&amp;</span><span class="number">3.1</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span><span class="number">2.7</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>-<span class="number">1.0</span>]);</code></pre></div>
<p>This method is particularly useful if combined with other methods, like
<a href="#method.map"><code>map</code></a>. This way, you can avoid moving the original
array if its elements are not <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/marker/trait.Copy.html" title="trait core::marker::Copy"><code>Copy</code></a>.</p>

<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="kw">let </span>strings = [<span class="string">"Ferris"</span>.to_string(), <span class="string">"♥"</span>.to_string(), <span class="string">"Rust"</span>.to_string()];
<span class="kw">let </span>is_ascii = strings.each_ref().map(|s| s.is_ascii());
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(is_ascii, [<span class="bool-val">true</span>, <span class="bool-val">false</span>, <span class="bool-val">true</span>]);

<span class="comment">// We can still access the original array: it has not been moved.
</span><span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(strings.len(), <span class="number">3</span>);</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.each_mut" class="method"><span class="rightside"><span class="since" title="Stable since Rust version 1.77.0">1.77.0</span> · <a class="src" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#662">Source</a></span><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.each_mut" class="fn">each_mut</a>(&amp;mut self) -&gt; [<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.reference.html">&amp;mut T</a>; <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">N</a>]</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Borrows each element mutably and returns an array of mutable references
with the same size as <code>self</code>.</p>
<h5 id="example-1"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#example-1">§</a>Example</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code>
<span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>floats = [<span class="number">3.1</span>, <span class="number">2.7</span>, -<span class="number">1.0</span>];
<span class="kw">let </span>float_refs: [<span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>f64; <span class="number">3</span>] = floats.each_mut();
<span class="kw-2">*</span>float_refs[<span class="number">0</span>] = <span class="number">0.0</span>;
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(float_refs, [<span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span><span class="number">0.0</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span><span class="number">2.7</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>-<span class="number">1.0</span>]);
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(floats, [<span class="number">0.0</span>, <span class="number">2.7</span>, -<span class="number">1.0</span>]);</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.split_array_ref" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#718">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.split_array_ref" class="fn">split_array_ref</a>&lt;const M: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt;(&amp;self) -&gt; (&amp;<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">[T; M]</a>, &amp;<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a>)</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>split_array</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Divides one array reference into two at an index.</p>
<p>The first will contain all indices from <code>[0, M)</code> (excluding
the index <code>M</code> itself) and the second will contain all
indices from <code>[M, N)</code> (excluding the index <code>N</code> itself).</p>
<h5 id="panics"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#panics">§</a>Panics</h5>
<p>Panics if <code>M &gt; N</code>.</p>
<h5 id="examples-1"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#examples-1">§</a>Examples</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="attr">#![feature(split_array)]

</span><span class="kw">let </span>v = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>];

{
   <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.split_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">0</span>&gt;();
   <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[]);
   <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
}

{
    <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.split_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">2</span>&gt;();
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>]);
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
}

{
    <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.split_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">6</span>&gt;();
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[]);
}</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.split_array_mut" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#751">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.split_array_mut" class="fn">split_array_mut</a>&lt;const M: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt;(&amp;mut self) -&gt; (&amp;mut <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">[T; M]</a>, &amp;mut <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a>)</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>split_array</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Divides one mutable array reference into two at an index.</p>
<p>The first will contain all indices from <code>[0, M)</code> (excluding
the index <code>M</code> itself) and the second will contain all
indices from <code>[M, N)</code> (excluding the index <code>N</code> itself).</p>
<h5 id="panics-1"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#panics-1">§</a>Panics</h5>
<p>Panics if <code>M &gt; N</code>.</p>
<h5 id="examples-2"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#examples-2">§</a>Examples</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="attr">#![feature(split_array)]

</span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>v = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>];
<span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.split_array_mut::&lt;<span class="number">2</span>&gt;();
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">0</span>][..]);
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>[<span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
left[<span class="number">1</span>] = <span class="number">2</span>;
right[<span class="number">1</span>] = <span class="number">4</span>;
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(v, [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.rsplit_array_ref" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#796">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.rsplit_array_ref" class="fn">rsplit_array_ref</a>&lt;const M: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt;(&amp;self) -&gt; (&amp;<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a>, &amp;<a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">[T; M]</a>)</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>split_array</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Divides one array reference into two at an index from the end.</p>
<p>The first will contain all indices from <code>[0, N - M)</code> (excluding
the index <code>N - M</code> itself) and the second will contain all
indices from <code>[N - M, N)</code> (excluding the index <code>N</code> itself).</p>
<h5 id="panics-2"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#panics-2">§</a>Panics</h5>
<p>Panics if <code>M &gt; N</code>.</p>
<h5 id="examples-3"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#examples-3">§</a>Examples</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="attr">#![feature(split_array)]

</span><span class="kw">let </span>v = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>];

{
   <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.rsplit_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">0</span>&gt;();
   <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
   <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[]);
}

{
    <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.rsplit_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">2</span>&gt;();
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>]);
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
}

{
    <span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.rsplit_array_ref::&lt;<span class="number">6</span>&gt;();
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[]);
    <span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);
}</code></pre></div></div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.rsplit_array_mut" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/array/mod.rs.html#829">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub fn <a href="#method.rsplit_array_mut" class="fn">rsplit_array_mut</a>&lt;const M: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt;(&amp;mut self) -&gt; (&amp;mut <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.slice.html">[T]</a>, &amp;mut <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.array.html">[T; M]</a>)</h4></section><span class="item-info"><div class="stab unstable"><span class="emoji">🔬</span><span>This is a nightly-only experimental API. (<code>split_array</code>)</span></div></span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Divides one mutable array reference into two at an index from the end.</p>
<p>The first will contain all indices from <code>[0, N - M)</code> (excluding
the index <code>N - M</code> itself) and the second will contain all
indices from <code>[N - M, N)</code> (excluding the index <code>N</code> itself).</p>
<h5 id="panics-3"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#panics-3">§</a>Panics</h5>
<p>Panics if <code>M &gt; N</code>.</p>
<h5 id="examples-4"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#examples-4">§</a>Examples</h5>
<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="attr">#![feature(split_array)]

</span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>v = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>];
<span class="kw">let </span>(left, right) = v.rsplit_array_mut::&lt;<span class="number">4</span>&gt;();
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(left, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>[<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">0</span>]);
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(right, <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>[<span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">0</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>][..]);
left[<span class="number">1</span>] = <span class="number">2</span>;
right[<span class="number">1</span>] = <span class="number">4</span>;
<span class="macro">assert_eq!</span>(v, [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>]);</code></pre></div></div></details></div></details><h2 id="trait-implementations" class="section-header">Trait Implementations<a href="#trait-implementations" class="anchor">§</a></h2><div id="trait-implementations-list"><details class="toggle implementors-toggle" open><summary><section id="impl-Clone-for-Frame1d%3CN%3E" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#391">Source</a><a href="#impl-Clone-for-Frame1d%3CN%3E" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;const N: <a class="primitive" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.usize.html">usize</a>&gt; device_<wbr>kit::<wbr>led_<wbr>strip</a></h2></div></div></nav><div class="sidebar-resizer" title="Drag to resize sidebar"></div><main><div class="width-limiter"><section id="main-content" class="content"><div class="main-heading"><div class="rustdoc-breadcrumbs"><a href="../index.html">device_kit</a>::<wbr><a href="index.html">led_strip</a></div><h1>Struct <span class="struct">Rgb888</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"></span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>pub struct Rgb888(<span class="comment">/* private fields */</span>);</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>8-bit-per-channel RGB color re-exported from the
<a href="https://docs.rs/embedded-graphics"><code>embedded-graphics</code></a> crate.</p>
<p>See <a href="../led2d/struct.Frame2d.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::Frame2d">Frame2d</a> for usage examples of <a href="struct.Rgb888.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::Rgb888"><code>Rgb888</code></a> and <a href="type.RGB8.html" title="type device_kit::led_strip::RGB8"><code>RGB8</code></a>.</p>
<p>Get named colors from <a href="colors/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip::colors"><code>colors</code></a> and convert to <code>Rgb888</code> with
<a href="trait.ToRgb888.html#tymethod.to_rgb888" title="method device_kit::led_strip::ToRgb888::to_rgb888"><code>ToRgb888::to_rgb888</code></a>.</p>
<p>Conversion to <a href="type.RGB8.html" title="type device_kit::led_strip::RGB8"><code>RGB8</code></a> via <a href="trait.ToRgb8.html#tymethod.to_rgb8" title="method device_kit::led_strip::ToRgb8::to_rgb8"><code>ToRgb8::to_rgb8</code></a>.</p>
<h2 id="embedded-graphics-documentation"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#embedded-graphics-documentation">§</a><a href="https://docs.rs/embedded-graphics/latest/embedded_graphics/pixelcolor/struct.Rgb888.html"><code>embedded-graphics</code></a> Documentation:</h2>
<p>Rgb888
color.</p>
<p>Use the methods provided by the [<code>RgbColor</code>] trait to access
individual color channels and predefined color constants.</p>
<p>See the <a href="super">module-level documentation</a> for more information about
conversion between this type and raw data.</p>
</div></details><h2 id="implementations" class="section-header">Implementations<a href="#implementations" class="anchor">§</a></h2><div id="implementations-list"><details class="toggle implementors-toggle" open><summary><section id="impl-Rgb888" class="impl"><a href="#impl-Rgb888" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl <a class="struct" href="struct.Rgb888.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::Rgb888">Rgb888</a><div class="where">where

Rgb888
color.
Too large channel values will be limited by setting the
unused most significant bits to zero.</p>

</div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#767-769">Source</a><a href="#impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T, U&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html" title="trait core::convert::Into">Into</a>&lt;U&gt; for T<div class="where">where

href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/primitive.u8.html">u8</a>&gt;;</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>8-bit-per-channel RGB color re-exported from the
<a href="https://docs.rs/smart-leds/latest/smart_leds/index.html"><code>smart_leds</code></a> crate.</p>
<p>Used in <a href="struct.Frame1d.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::Frame1d"><code>Frame1d</code></a> and <a href="../led2d/struct.Frame2d.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::Frame2d">Frame2d</a> for pixel colors.</p>
<p>See <a href="colors/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip::colors"><code>colors</code></a> for the predefined color list.</p>
<p>Conversion to <a href="struct.Rgb888.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::Rgb888"><code>Rgb888</code></a> via <a href="trait.ToRgb888.html#tymethod.to_rgb888" title="method device_kit::led_strip::ToRgb888::to_rgb888"><code>ToRgb888::to_rgb888</code></a>.</p>
<h2 id="smart_leds-documentation"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#smart_leds-documentation">§</a><a href="https://docs.rs/smart-leds/latest/smart_leds/type.RGB8.html"><code>smart_leds</code></a> Documentation:</h2>
<p>8-bit RGB</p>
<p>The colorspace is technically undefined, but generally sRGB is assumed.</p>

class="sidebar-crate"><h2><a href="../device_kit/index.html">device_<wbr>kit</a><span class="version">0.0.1-alpha</span></h2></div><div class="sidebar-elems"><section id="rustdoc-toc"><h2 class="location"><a href="#">led2d</a></h2><h3><a href="#">Sections</a></h3><ul class="block top-toc"><li><a href="#fields-1" title="Fields">Fields</a></li><li><a href="#current-limiting" title="Drag to resize sidebar"></div><main><div class="width-limiter"><section id="main-content" class="content"><div class="main-heading"><div class="rustdoc-breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">device_kit</a></div><h1>Macro <span class="macro">led2d</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../src/device_kit/led2d.rs.html#1048-1050">Source</a> </span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>macro_rules! led2d {
    ($($tt:tt)*) =&gt; { ... };
}</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Macro to generate an LED-panel struct type (includes syntax details). See <a href="led2d/led2d_generated/struct.Led2dGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::led2d_generated::Led2dGenerated"><code>Led2dGenerated</code></a> for a sample of a generated type.</p>
<p><strong>See the <a href="led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d">led2d module</a> for usage examples.</strong></p>
<h2 id="fields-1"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#fields-1">§</a>Fields</h2>
<p><strong>Required fields:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><code>pin</code> — GPIO pin for LED data</li>
<li><code>led_layout</code> — LED strip physical layout (see <a href="led2d/layout/struct.LedLayout.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::layout::LedLayout"><code>LedLayout</code></a>); this defines the panel size</li>
<li><code>font</code> — Built-in font variant (see <a href="led2d/enum.Led2dFont.html" title="enum device_kit::led2d::Led2dFont"><code>Led2dFont</code></a>), e.g. <code>Led2dFont::Font4x6Trim</code></li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>led_layout</code> value must be a const so its dimensions can be derived at compile time.</p>
<p><strong>Optional fields:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><code>pio</code> — PIO resource to use (default: <code>PIO0</code>)</li>
<li><code>dma</code> — DMA channel (default: <code>DMA_CH0</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_current</code> — Electrical current budget (default: 250 mA)</li>
<li><code>gamma</code> — Color curve (default: <code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_frames</code> — Maximum number of animation frames for the generated strip (default: 16 frames)</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="current-limiting"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#current-limiting">§</a>Current Limiting</h2>
<p>The <code>max_current</code> field automatically scales brightness to stay within your electrical current budget.</p>
<p>Each WS2812 LED is assumed to draw 60 mA at full brightness. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>16 LEDs × 60 mA = 960 mA at full brightness</li>
<li>With <code>max_current: Current::Milliamps(1000)</code>, all LEDs fit at 100% brightness</li>
<li>With the default electrical current limit (250 mA), the generated <code>MAX_BRIGHTNESS</code> limits LEDs to ~26% brightness</li>
</ul>
<p>The electrical current limit is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<p><strong>Powering LEDs from the Pico’s pin 40 (VBUS):</strong> Pin 40 is the USB 5 V rail pass-through, but the Pico itself has practical electrical current limits — the USB connector, cable, and internal circuitry aren’t designed for heavy loads. Small LED panels (a few hundred mA) can usually power from pin 40 with a decent USB supply; for larger loads (1 A+), use a separate 5 V supply and share ground with the Pico.</p>
<h2 id="color-correction-gamma"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#color-correction-gamma">§</a>Color Correction (Gamma)</h2>
<p>The <code>gamma</code> field applies a color response curve to make colors look more natural:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="led_strip/enum.Gamma.html#variant.Linear" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Linear"><code>Gamma::Linear</code></a> — No correction (raw values)</li>
<li><a href="led_strip/enum.Gamma.html#variant.Gamma2_2" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Gamma2_2"><code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code></a> — sRGB-like curve (default; often looks most natural)</li>
</ul>
<p>The gamma curve is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<h2 id="related-macros"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#related-macros">§</a>Related Macros</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="macro.led_strips.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strips"><code>led_strips!</code></a> — Alternative macro to share a PIO resource with other panels or LED strips (includes examples)</li>
<li><a href="led_strip/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a> — For 1-dimensional LED strips</li>
</ul>
</div></details></section></div></main></body></html>

class="width-limiter"><section id="main-content" class="content"><div class="main-heading"><div class="rustdoc-breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">device_kit</a></div><h1>Macro <span     ($($tt:tt)*) =&gt; { ... };
}</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Macro to generate an LED-strip struct type (includes syntax details). See
<a href="led_strip/led_strip_generated/struct.LedStripGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::led_strip_generated::LedStripGenerated"><code>LedStripGenerated</code></a> for a sample of a generated type.</p>
<p><strong>See the <a href="led_strip/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led_strip">led_strip module documentation</a> for usage examples.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Required fields:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><code>pin</code> — GPIO pin for LED data</li>
<li><code>len</code> — Number of LEDs</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Optional fields:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><code>pio</code> — PIO resource (default: <code>PIO0</code>)</li>
<li><code>dma</code> — DMA channel (default: <code>DMA_CH0</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_current</code> — Electrical current budget (default: 250 mA)</li>
<li><code>gamma</code> — Color curve (default: <code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_frames</code> — Maximum number of animation frames (default: 16 frames)</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="current-limiting"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#current-limiting">§</a>Current Limiting</h2>
<p>The <code>max_current</code> field automatically scales brightness to stay within your electrical current budget.</p>
<p>Each WS2812 LED is assumed to draw 60 mA at full brightness. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>16 LEDs × 60 mA = 960 mA at full brightness</li>

<li>With the default electrical current limit (250 mA), the generated <code>MAX_BRIGHTNESS</code> limits LEDs to ~26% brightness</li>
</ul>
<p>The electrical current limit is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<p><strong>Powering LEDs from the Pico’s pin 40 (VBUS):</strong> Pin 40 is the USB 5 V rail pass-through, but the Pico itself has practical electrical current limits — the USB connector, cable, and internal circuitry aren’t designed for heavy loads. Small LED panels (a few hundred mA) can usually power from pin 40 with a decent USB supply; for larger loads (1 A+), use a separate 5 V supply and share ground with the Pico.</p>
<h2 id="color-correction-gamma"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#color-correction-gamma">§</a>Color Correction (Gamma)</h2>

</ul>
<p>The gamma curve is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>

href="#example-connect-three-led-stripspanels-to-one-pio-resource" title="Example: Connect Three LED Strips/Panels to One PIO Resource">Example: Connect Three LED Strips/Panels to One PIO href="#required-fields-per-strippanel" title="Required Fields per Strip/Panel">Required Fields per Strip/Panel</a></li><li><a href="#optional-fields-per-strippanel" title="Optional Fields per title="Drag to resize sidebar"></div><main><div class="width-limiter"><section id="main-content" class="content"><div class="main-heading"><div class="rustdoc-breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">device_kit</a></div><h1>Macro <span class="macro">led_<wbr>strips</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../src/device_kit/led_strip.rs.html#987-989">Source</a> </span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>macro_rules! led_strips {
    ($($tt:tt)*) =&gt; { ... };
}</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Macro to generate multiple LED strip and panel struct types that share a single
<a href="index.html#glossary" title="mod device_kit">PIO resource</a> (includes syntax details).</p>
<p>This page provides the primary documentation and examples for configuring strip/panel
groups that share a PIO resource.</p>
<p><strong>After reading the examples below, see also:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="led_strip/led_strip_generated/struct.LedStripGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led_strip::led_strip_generated::LedStripGenerated"><code>LedStripGenerated</code></a> — Sample LED <strong>strip</strong> type showing all methods and associated constants</li>
<li><a href="led2d/led2d_generated/struct.Led2dGenerated.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::led2d_generated::Led2dGenerated"><code>Led2dGenerated</code></a> — Sample LED <strong>panel</strong> type showing all methods and associated constants</li>
<li><a href="macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a> — Alternative macro to generate a single LED strip type. Consumes a PIO resource.</li>
<li><a href="led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> — Alternative macro to generate a single LED panel type. Consumes a PIO resource.</li>
</ul>
<p>Use this macro when your project has multiple LED strips or panels
that should share a single PIO resource.
If you only need a single strip or panel, prefer <a href="macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a>
or <a href="macro.led2d.html" title="macro device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> for simpler configuration.</p>
<p>We’ll start with a complete example below, then describe the required and
optional fields in detail.</p>
<h2 id="example-connect-three-led-stripspanels-to-one-pio-resource"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#example-connect-three-led-stripspanels-to-one-pio-resource">§</a>Example: Connect Three LED Strips/Panels to One PIO Resource</h2>
<p>This example creates three LED strips/panels on GPIO0, GPIO3, and GPIO4,
all sharing PIO0. It demonstrates showing a pattern on the first two strips
and animating text on the 2D panel.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO0 strip preview" /></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO3 strip preview" /></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="GPIO4 panel preview" /></p>

<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="kw">use </span>device_kit::{<span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>, led2d::Frame2d, led2d::Led2dFont, led2d::layout::LedLayout, led_strip::{Current, Frame1d, Gamma, colors, led_strips}};
<span class="kw">use </span>embassy_time::Duration;

<span class="comment">// Our 2D panel is two 12x4 panels stacked vertically.
</span><span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X4: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">48</span>, <span class="number">12</span>, <span class="number">4</span>&gt; = LedLayout::serpentine_column_major();
<span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X8: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">96</span>, <span class="number">12</span>, <span class="number">8</span>&gt; = LED_LAYOUT_12X4.combine_v(LED_LAYOUT_12X4);
<span class="kw">const </span>LED_LAYOUT_12X8_ROTATED: LedLayout&lt;<span class="number">96</span>, <span class="number">8</span>, <span class="number">12</span>&gt; = LED_LAYOUT_12X8.rotate_cw();

<span class="macro">led_strips!</span> {
    pio: PIO0,                          <span class="comment">// Optional; defaults to PIO0.
    </span>LedStrips0 {                        <span class="comment">// Name for this group of LED strips/panels. Can provide visibility modifier
        // 1. a 8-LED strip on GPIO0
        </span>Gpio0LedStrip: {                <span class="comment">// Exact struct name for this strip.
            </span>pin: PIN_0,                 <span class="comment">// GPIO pin for LED data signal.
            </span>len: <span class="number">8</span>,                     <span class="comment">// 8 LEDs on this strip.
            </span>max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">25</span>), <span class="comment">// Every strip/panel requires an electrical current budget.
        </span>},
        <span class="comment">// 2. a 48-LED strip on GPIO3
        </span>Gpio3LedStrip: {
            pin: PIN_3,
            len: <span class="number">48</span>,
            max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">75</span>),
            gamma: Gamma::Gamma2_2,     <span class="comment">// Optional; color correction (default, Gamma::Gamma2_2).
            </span>max_frames: <span class="number">1</span>,              <span class="comment">// Optional; default 16 frames.
            </span>dma: DMA_CH11,              <span class="comment">// Optional; auto-assigned by strip order.
        </span>},
        <span class="comment">// 3. a 96-LED 2D panel on GPIO4
        </span>Gpio4Led2d: {
            pin: PIN_4,
            len: <span class="number">96</span>,
            max_current: Current::Milliamps(<span class="number">250</span>),
            max_frames: <span class="number">2</span>,
            led2d: {                    <span class="comment">// Optional panel configuration for 2D displays.
                </span>led_layout: LED_LAYOUT_12X8_ROTATED, <span class="comment">// Two 12×4 panels stacked and rotated.
                </span>font: Led2dFont::Font4x6Trim, <span class="comment">// 4x6 pixel font without the usual 1 pixel spacing.
            </span>}
        },
    }
}

<span class="kw">async fn </span>example(spawner: Spawner) -&gt; <span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>&lt;Infallible&gt; {
    <span class="kw">let </span>p = embassy_rp::init(Default::default());

    <span class="comment">// Create instances of two LED strips and one panel.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span>(gpio0_led_strip, gpio3_led_strip, gpio4_led2d) = LedStrips0::new(
        p.PIO0, p.PIN_0, p.DMA_CH0, p.PIN_3, p.DMA_CH11, p.PIN_4, p.DMA_CH2, spawner,
    )<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="macro">info!</span>(<span class="string">"Setting GPIO0 to white, GPIO3 to alternating blue/gray, GPIO4 to Go Go animation"</span>);

    <span class="comment">// Turn on all-white on GPIO0 strip.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span>frame_gpio0 = Frame1d::filled(colors::WHITE);
    gpio0_led_strip.write_frame(frame_gpio0).<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>; <span class="comment">// Display the frame (until replaced)

    // Alternate blue/gray on GPIO3 strip.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_gpio3 = Frame1d::new();
    <span class="kw">for </span>pixel_index <span class="kw">in </span><span class="number">0</span>..Gpio3LedStrip::LEN {
        frame_gpio3[pixel_index] = [colors::BLUE, colors::GRAY][pixel_index % <span class="number">2</span>];
    }
    gpio3_led_strip.write_frame(frame_gpio3).<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>;  <span class="comment">// Display the frame (until replaced)

    // Animate "Go Go" text on GPIO4 2D panel.
    </span><span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_go_top = Frame2d::new();
    gpio4_led2d.write_text_to_frame(<span class="string">"Go"</span>, <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[], <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>frame_go_top)<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="kw">let </span><span class="kw-2">mut </span>frame_go_bottom = Frame2d::new();
    gpio4_led2d.write_text_to_frame(
        <span class="string">"\nGo"</span>,
        <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>[colors::HOT_PINK, colors::LIME],
        <span class="kw-2">&amp;mut </span>frame_go_bottom,
    )<span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="kw">let </span>frame_duration = Duration::from_secs(<span class="number">1</span>);
    gpio4_led2d
        .animate([
            (frame_go_top, frame_duration),
            (frame_go_bottom, frame_duration),
        ])
        .<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>; <span class="comment">// Loop animation (until replaced)

    </span>future::pending::&lt;<span class="prelude-ty">Result</span>&lt;Infallible&gt;&gt;().<span class="kw">await </span><span class="comment">// Run forever
</span>}</code></pre></div><h2 id="configuration"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#configuration">§</a>Configuration</h2><h3 id="shared-pio-resource"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#shared-pio-resource">§</a>Shared PIO Resource</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>pio</code> — PIO peripheral to use (default: <code>PIO0</code>). This consumes one PIO resource for the
group and is shared across all strips/panels in the macro invocation.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="required-fields-per-strippanel"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#required-fields-per-strippanel">§</a>Required Fields per Strip/Panel</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>pin</code> — GPIO pin for LED data</li>
<li><code>len</code> — Number of LEDs (pixels)</li>
<li><code>max_current</code> — Electrical current budget per strip (required; no default)</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="optional-fields-per-strippanel"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#optional-fields-per-strippanel">§</a>Optional Fields per Strip/Panel</h3>
<ul>
<li><code>dma</code> — DMA channel (default: auto-assigned by strip order)</li>
<li><code>gamma</code> — Gamma correction curve (default: <code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code>)</li>
<li><code>max_frames</code> — Maximum number of animation frames (default: 16 frames)</li>
<li><code>led2d</code> — Marks this strip as a 2D LED panel and enables 2D rendering support (optional, see below).
Detailed 2D rendering, examples, and animation support are documented
in the <a href="led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d</code> module</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="2d-panel-configuration-led2d"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#2d-panel-configuration-led2d">§</a>2D Panel Configuration (<code>led2d</code>)</h3>
<p>If a strip represents a rectangular LED panel rather than a linear strip,
add a <code>led2d</code> configuration block to describe its geometry.</p>
<p>Required fields:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>led_layout</code> — Physical layout mapping (defines the panel size). See <a href="led2d/layout/struct.LedLayout.html" title="struct device_kit::led2d::layout::LedLayout"><code>LedLayout</code></a> for details.</li>
<li><code>font</code> — Built-in font for text rendering. See <a href="led2d/enum.Led2dFont.html" title="enum device_kit::led2d::Led2dFont"><code>Led2dFont</code></a> for available fonts.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>led_layout</code> value must be a const so its dimensions can be derived at compile time.</p>
<h2 id="capacity-and-board-capabilities"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#capacity-and-board-capabilities">§</a>Capacity and Board Capabilities</h2>
<p>The <code>led_strips!</code> macro is designed to <strong>fully utilize the PIO resources</strong>
of supported Pico boards.</p>
<p>Each <code>led_strips!</code> invocation can drive up to <strong>4 LED strips or panels</strong>
while sharing a single PIO resource. This lets you consolidate multiple
LED outputs efficiently instead of consuming one PIO per strip.</p>
<p>Each invocation consumes exactly one PIO resource.</p>
<p>On supported boards, this enables the maximum practical LED capacity:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pico 1</strong> provides <strong>2 PIO resources</strong>, allowing up to <strong>8 LED strips or panels</strong></li>
<li><strong>Pico 2</strong> provides <strong>3 PIO resources</strong>, allowing up to <strong>12 LED strips or panels</strong></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="current-limiting"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#current-limiting">§</a>Current Limiting</h2>
<p>The <code>max_current</code> field automatically scales brightness to stay within your electrical current budget.</p>
<p>Each WS2812 LED is assumed to draw 60 mA at full brightness. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>16 LEDs × 60 mA = 960 mA at full brightness</li>
<li>With <code>max_current: Current::Milliamps(1000)</code>, all LEDs fit at 100% brightness</li>
<li>With the default electrical current limit (250 mA), the generated <code>MAX_BRIGHTNESS</code> limits LEDs to ~26% brightness</li>
</ul>
<p>The electrical current limit is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<p><strong>Powering LEDs from the Pico’s pin 40 (VBUS):</strong> Pin 40 is the USB 5 V rail pass-through, but the Pico itself has practical electrical current limits — the USB connector, cable, and internal circuitry aren’t designed for heavy loads. Small LED panels (a few hundred mA) can usually power from pin 40 with a decent USB supply; for larger loads (1 A+), use a separate 5 V supply and share ground with the Pico.</p>
<h2 id="color-correction-gamma"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#color-correction-gamma">§</a>Color Correction (Gamma)</h2>
<p>The <code>gamma</code> field applies a color response curve to make colors look more natural:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="led_strip/enum.Gamma.html#variant.Linear" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Linear"><code>Gamma::Linear</code></a> — No correction (raw values)</li>
<li><a href="led_strip/enum.Gamma.html#variant.Gamma2_2" title="variant device_kit::led_strip::Gamma::Gamma2_2"><code>Gamma::Gamma2_2</code></a> — sRGB-like curve (default; often looks most natural)</li>
</ul>
<p>The gamma curve is baked into a compile-time lookup table, so it has no runtime cost.</p>
<h2 id="related-macros"><a class="doc-anchor" href="#related-macros">§</a>Related Macros</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href="macro.led_strip.html" title="macro device_kit::led_strip"><code>led_strip!</code></a> — For a single 1-dimensional LED strip (includes examples)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="led2d/index.html" title="mod device_kit::led2d"><code>led2d!</code></a> — For 2-dimensional LED panels</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div></details></section></div></main></body></html>

(<code>clone_to_uninit</code>)</span></div></span><div class='docblock'>Performs copy-assignment from <code>self</code> to <code>dest</code>. <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/clone/trait.CloneToUninit.html#tymethod.clone_to_uninit">Read more</a></div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-From%3CT%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#785">Source</a><a href="#impl-From%3CT%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt; for T</h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.from" class="method trait-impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#788">Source</a><a href="#method.from" class="anchor">§</a><h4 class="code-header">fn <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html#tymethod.from" class="fn">from</a>(t: T) -&gt; T</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Returns the argument unchanged.</p>
</div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#767-769">Source</a><a href="#impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T, U&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html" title="trait core::convert::Into">Into</a>&lt;U&gt; for T<div class="where">where
    U: <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt;,</div></h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.into" class="method trait-impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#777">Source</a><a href="#method.into" class="anchor">§</a><h4 class="code-header">fn <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html#tymethod.into" class="fn">into</a>(self) -&gt; U</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Calls <code>U::from(self)</code>.</p>
<p>That is, this conversion is whatever the implementation of
<code><a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt; for U</code> chooses to do.</p>

id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../../src/device_kit/rfid.rs.html#72-74">Source</a> </span></div><pre class="rust item-decl"><code>pub struct Rfid&lt;'a&gt; { <span class="comment">/* private fields */</span> }</code></pre><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>A device abstraction for an RFID reader using the MFRC522 chip.</p>

<div class="example-wrap"><pre class="rust rust-example-rendered"><code><span class="kw">use </span>device_kit::rfid::{Rfid, RfidEvent, RfidStatic};

<span class="kw">async fn </span>example(
    p: embassy_rp::Peripherals,
    spawner: embassy_executor::Spawner,
) -&gt; device_kit::Result&lt;()&gt; {
    <span class="kw">static </span>RFID_STATIC: RfidStatic = Rfid::new_static();
    <span class="kw">let </span>rfid = Rfid::new(
        <span class="kw-2">&amp;</span>RFID_STATIC,
        p.SPI0,
        p.PIN_2,
        p.PIN_3,
        p.PIN_0,
        p.DMA_CH0,
        p.DMA_CH1,
        p.PIN_1,
        p.PIN_4,
        spawner,
    )
    .<span class="kw">await</span><span class="question-mark">?</span>;

    <span class="kw">loop </span>{
        <span class="kw">let </span>RfidEvent::CardDetected { uid } = rfid.wait_for_tap().<span class="kw">await</span>;
        <span class="macro">defmt::info!</span>(<span class="string">"RFID uid: {:?}"</span>, uid);
    }
}</code></pre></div></div></details><h2 id="implementations" class="section-header">Implementations<a href="#implementations" class="anchor">§</a></h2><div id="implementations-list"><details class="toggle implementors-toggle" open><summary><section id="impl-Rfid%3C'_%3E" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/rfid.rs.html#76-122">Source</a><a href="#impl-Rfid%3C'_%3E" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl <a class="struct" href="struct.Rfid.html" title="struct device_kit::rfid::Rfid">Rfid</a>&lt;'_&gt;</h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.new_static" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/rfid.rs.html#79-81">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub const fn <a href="#method.new_static" class="fn">new_static</a>() -&gt; <a class="type" href="type.RfidStatic.html" title="type device_kit::rfid::RfidStatic">RfidStatic</a></h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Create static channel resources for the RFID reader</p>
</div></details><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.new" class="method"><a class="src rightside" href="../../src/device_kit/rfid.rs.html#86-116">Source</a><h4 class="code-header">pub async fn <a href="#method.new" class="fn">new</a>&lt;Sck, Mosi, Miso, Dma0, Dma1, Cs, Rst&gt;(
    rfid_static: &amp;'static <a class="type" href="type.RfidStatic.html" title="type device_kit::rfid::RfidStatic">RfidStatic</a>,
    spi: Peri&lt;'static, SPI0&gt;,

    spawner: Spawner,
) -&gt; <a class="type" href="../type.Result.html" title="type device_kit::Result">Result</a>&lt;Self&gt;<div class="where">where
    Sck: Pin + ClkPin&lt;SPI0&gt;,
    Mosi: Pin + MosiPin&lt;SPI0&gt;,
    Miso: Pin + MisoPin&lt;SPI0&gt;,
    Dma0: Channel,
    Dma1: Channel,
    Cs: Pin,
    Rst: Pin,</div></h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Create a new RFID reader device abstraction</p>
<p>Note: Currently hardcoded to SPI0. All peripherals must have ’static lifetime.</p>

</div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#767-769">Source</a><a href="#impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T, U&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html" title="trait core::convert::Into">Into</a>&lt;U&gt; for T<div class="where">where

<p>That is, this conversion is whatever the implementation of
<code><a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt; for U</code> chooses to do.</p>

(<code>clone_to_uninit</code>)</span></div></span><div class='docblock'>Performs copy-assignment from <code>self</code> to <code>dest</code>. <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/clone/trait.CloneToUninit.html#tymethod.clone_to_uninit">Read more</a></div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-From%3CT%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#785">Source</a><a href="#impl-From%3CT%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt; for T</h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.from" class="method trait-impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#788">Source</a><a href="#method.from" class="anchor">§</a><h4 class="code-header">fn <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html#tymethod.from" class="fn">from</a>(t: T) -&gt; T</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Returns the argument unchanged.</p>
</div></details></div></details><details class="toggle implementors-toggle"><summary><section id="impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#767-769">Source</a><a href="#impl-Into%3CU%3E-for-T" class="anchor">§</a><h3 class="code-header">impl&lt;T, U&gt; <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html" title="trait core::convert::Into">Into</a>&lt;U&gt; for T<div class="where">where
    U: <a class="trait" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt;,</div></h3></section></summary><div class="impl-items"><details class="toggle method-toggle" open><summary><section id="method.into" class="method trait-impl"><a class="src rightside" href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/src/core/convert/mod.rs.html#777">Source</a><a href="#method.into" class="anchor">§</a><h4 class="code-header">fn <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.Into.html#tymethod.into" class="fn">into</a>(self) -&gt; U</h4></section></summary><div class="docblock"><p>Calls <code>U::from(self)</code>.</p>
<p>That is, this conversion is whatever the implementation of
<code><a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.92.0/core/convert/trait.From.html" title="trait core::convert::From">From</a>&lt;T&gt; for U</code> chooses to do.</p>

path</button></h1><rustdoc-toolbar></rustdoc-toolbar><span class="sub-heading"><a class="src" href="../../src/device_kit/servo.rs.html#1-208">Source</a> </span></div><details class="toggle top-doc" open><summary class="hideme"><span>Expand description</span></summary><div class="docblock"><p>A device abstraction for SG90 servo motors.</p>
<p>This module provides a simple interface for controlling hobby positional servo motors
like the SG90.</p>
<p>Use the <a href="macro.servo_even.html" title="macro device_kit::servo::servo_even"><code>servo_even!</code></a> or <a href="macro.servo_odd.html" title="macro device_kit::servo::servo_odd"><code>servo_odd!</code></a> macros for even or odd GPIO pins respectively.</p>
<p>See <a href="struct.Servo.html" title="struct device_kit::servo::Servo"><code>Servo</code></a> for usage examples.</p>
</div></details><h2 id="reexports" class="section-header">Re-exports<a href="#reexports" class="anchor">§</a></h2><dl class="item-table reexports"><dt id="reexport.servo"><code>pub use crate::<a class="mod" href="index.html" title="mod device_kit::servo">servo</a>;</code></dt></dl><h2 id="macros" class="section-header">Macros<a href="#macros" class="anchor">§</a></h2><dl class="item-table"><dt><a class="macro" href="macro.servo_even.html" title="macro device_kit::servo::servo_even">servo_<wbr>even</a></dt><dd>Create a servo on an even-numbered GPIO pin (0, 2, 4, 6…).</dd><dt><a class="macro" href="macro.servo_odd.html" title="macro device_kit::servo::servo_odd">servo_<wbr>odd</a></dt><dd>Create a servo on an odd-numbered GPIO pin (1, 3, 5, 7…).</dd></dl><h2 id="structs" class="section-header">Structs<a href="#structs" class="anchor">§</a></h2><dl class="item-table"><dt><a class="struct" href="struct.Servo.html" title="struct device_kit::servo::Servo">Servo</a></dt><dd>A device abstraction for SG90 servo motors.</dd></dl><h2 id="enums" class="section-header">Enums<a href="#enums" class="anchor">§</a></h2><dl class="item-table"><dt><a class="enum" href="enum.ServoChannel.html" title="enum device_kit::servo::ServoChannel">Servo<wbr>Channel</a></dt><dd>Which PWM channel the servo is on.</dd></dl></section></div></main></body></html>

title="WrappingAs">WrappingAs</a></li><li><a href="#impl-WrappingCastFrom%3CSrc%3E-for-Dst" title="WrappingCastFrom&#60;Src&#62;">WrappingCastFrom&#60;Src&#62;</a></li></ul></section><div id="rustdoc-modnav"><h2><a href="index.html">In device_<wbr>kit::<wbr>servo</a></h2></div></div></nav><div class="sidebar-resizer" title="Drag to resize sidebar"></div><main><div href="index.html">servo</a></div><h1>Struct <span class="struct">Servo</span>&nbsp;<button id="copy-path" title="Copy item path to clipboard">Copy item
